'''Washington Curran Whitthorne''' (April 19, 1825 &ndash; September 21, 1891) was a [[Tennessee]] [[Lawyer|attorney]], [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] [[politician]], and an [[Adjutant General]] in the [[Confederate Army]].

==Early life and career==
Whitthorne was born near [[Petersburg, Tennessee]] in [[Marshall County, Tennessee|Marshall County]].<ref name=B>United States Congress's pg. 109</ref> One day when Whitthorne was young [[James K. Polk]] stayed at his family's home.<ref name=A>Bar Association of Tennessee's pp. 126-129</ref> Polk saw how bright he was and asked, "What are you going to make of this boy?" His father replied "I am going to make him the President of the United States."<ref name=A></ref> Polk then told them to send the boy to [[Columbia, Tennessee|Columbia]] and he would make him a lawyer. He attended Campbell Academy in [[Lebanon, Tennessee]] and subsequently  East Tennessee College (now the [[University of Tennessee]]) where he graduated in 1843.<ref name=B></ref> He subsequently studied law and was admitted to the [[Bar (law)|bar]] in 1845, serving in various governmental positions, and working for [[James K. Polk]] until he entered private practice in 1848 in [[Columbia, Tennessee]]. On July 4, 1848 Whitthorne married Matilda Jane Campbell a cousin of Polk.<ref name=A></ref>

He was elected to serve in the [[Tennessee State Senate]] from 1855 to 1858. Whitthorne was then elected [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker]] of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]] from 1859 to 1861.<ref name=A></ref>

==Civil War service==
In 1861 he became [[Adjutant General]] of Tennessee for the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]], and served that post through the end of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. He also served on the staff of [[History of Confederate States Army Generals|generals]] [[Robert Anderson (Civil War)|Robert Anderson]], [[Marcus Joseph Wright]], [[Samuel P. Carter]], and [[William J. Hardee]].<ref name=B></ref>

==Postbellum career==
In 1870 his full [[civil rights]] were restored to him when [[President Andrew Johnson]] had him pardoned, and that year he began a campaign for the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref name=C></ref>  He won the election successful, and would eventually serv six consecutive terms during his initial service in the House, chairing the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|House Committee on Naval Affairs]] from 1875 to 1881.<ref name=C>The National Cyclopedia of American Biography pg. 140</ref>

Upon the resignation of Senator [[Howell E. Jackson]], Whitthorne was appointed to the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] by [[governor of Tennessee]] [[William B. Bate]] and then subsequently elected to the balance of the term by the [[Tennessee General Assembly]], serving in the Senate from April 16, 1886 to March 3, 1887.<ref name=B></ref>  Following his Senate service he served two more subsequent consecutive terms in the U.S. House, from 1887 to 1891.  After serving in the [[House of Representatives]] Whitthorne returned to [[Columbia, Tennessee|Columbia]] and died there later in 1891, being interred at Rose Hill Cemetery.<ref name=C></ref>  Whitthorne Middle School in Columbia, formerly Whitthorne Junior High School, is named in his honor.

